\subsubsection{Cross-trial coordination on $\tau^2$-bench telecom: pass$^k$ as a coordination metric}
\label{sec:eval:results:tau2}

We adapt $\tau^2$-bench's telecom domain~\cite{tau2bench2025} as a
fourth evaluation cell.  $\tau^2$-bench is a state-validated tool-use
benchmark whose scorer compares the agent's final database state
against a target state produced by replaying a reference action
sequence; redundant or wrong-state write calls register as evaluation
failures directly, so the redundancy reduction ET-MCP targets has
intrinsic user-visible value here in a way it does not on
Silo-Bench or our internal benchmarks.  The headline metric is
\textsc{pass}$^k$: the fraction of tasks where \emph{all $k$
independent trials} succeed.  pass$^k$ is sensitive to coordination
because, by construction, a single trial-level failure on any of the
$k$ trials drops a task out of the pass$^k$ pool.

\paragraph{Setup.}
We adapt the four ET-MCP coordination protocols of
\S\ref{sec:eval:ablations} to $\tau^2$-bench's single-agent interface by
making the ET-MCP trace store \emph{task-scoped across trials} (the
store allocates when a task starts, persists across the $k$ trials,
and tears down at task close).  This lets the four protocols differ
only in what they expose to trial $j$ of the data accumulated by
trials $1,\ldots,j-1$ of the same task.  The same writer-side selection
policy (failure\_only: record \textsc{failed\_path} on any errored
tool call) is used by all three coordinated protocols; only the
reader-side interface differs:
%
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{no\_coord}: each trial gets an isolated, fresh store;
    no cross-trial reads or writes.
  \item \textbf{push\_scratchpad}: cross-trial shared store; every
    event from prior trials is dumped wholesale into the agent's
    per-turn system prompt (a CA-MCP-style unfiltered context push).
  \item \textbf{message\_passing}: cross-trial shared store;
    prior-trial events are summarized into a single fixed-format
    handoff message attached as a system note (push, fixed schema).
  \item \textbf{et\_mcp}: cross-trial shared store; agents pull
    relevant prior-trial events on demand via a TF-IDF query against
    the current input, top-$k$ events returned as a
    \texttt{<peer\_warnings>} block.
\end{itemize}
%
This is the same four-cell design as the Silo-Bench and TravelPlanner
factorial ablations of \S\ref{sec:eval:results:silo} and
\S\ref{sec:eval:results:travelplanner-isolation}; what changes is the
benchmark's evaluation semantics, where the redundancy metric is
intrinsic to the official pass$^k$ score rather than a process-only
diagnostic.

